nd individualism. Through Walt Whitman, Emily Dickinson, William S. Burroughs, and Thomas Pynchon, Haines brings to light a radically different version of the American dream—one in which political subjects value an organization of social life that includes democratic self-governance, egalitarian cooperation, and communal property.A Desire Called America brings utopian studies and the critical discourse of biopolitics to bear upon each other, suggesting that utopia might be less another place than our best hope for confronting authoritarianism, neoliberalism, and a resurgent exclusionary nationalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAmerican literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aExceptionalismzUnited States. 0aPolitics in literature. 0aUtopias in literature. 0aUtopiaszUnited States. 4aAmerican Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aPhilosophy & Theory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh  aAmerican exceptionalism.  aBiopolitics.  aCommons.  aEmily Dickinson.  aThomas Pynchon.  aUtopia.  aWalt Whitman.  aWilliam Burroughs.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311072273440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823286973zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823286973423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823286973/original  a978-3-11-072273-4  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK